[{:rule-id "rule-ai", :item {:feed-id "hn-frontpage", :item-id "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48063548", :title "Show HN: Git for AI Agents", :link "https://github.com/regent-vcs/re_gent", :published-at #inst "2026-05-08T14:15:36.000-00:00", :content "hi guys. been working on something i think is fundamentally missing in today's workflow with ai agents. vcs. i find myself struggling with questions that agents can't answer like \"why did you do it?\", \"when did u delete this folder? why?\", etc. or trying to /rewind (after a /compact...) or basically `bisect` to find when and why something was done by the agent in the current / previous session. just like git did for code, i think we are the same core capabilities with ai agents so... i developed an open source solution for that (currently supporting claude code) would love to get feedback, contribution or maybe other ideas or solutions you find for those problems. Comments URL: https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48063548 Points: 59 # Comments: 32"}, :excerpts [{:text "... source solution for that (currently supporting claude code) would love to get feedback, contribution or...", :matched-terms ["claude"], :source :content}]} {:rule-id "clojure-db", :item {:feed-id "planet-clojure", :item-id "https://www.bigconfig.ai/blog/solving-software-delivery-for-the-vibecoder-without-breaking-production/", :title "Solving Software Delivery for the \"Vibecoder\" Without Breaking Production", :link "https://www.bigconfig.ai/blog/solving-software-delivery-for-the-vibecoder-without-breaking-production/", :published-at #inst "2026-05-08T00:00:00.000-00:00", :content "Software delivery used to be a game of manual configuration, complex YAML files, and a prayer that your local environment matched production. But the era of the “Vibecoder”—the developer who uses plain-English prompts and LLMs to manifest software—is here. The challenge? How do we let an AI agent handle infrastructure without it becoming a “bull in a code-shop” scenario? Recently, a debate sparked between myself and two former colleagues from my Zalando days, Thomas Bradford and Artur Mkrtchyan (Co-founder of Softr.io). While Thomas raised valid skepticism about AI coding patterns, Artur hit on a critical “real-world” nerve: The 95% Problem. Artur argued that while a safe setup sounds great in theory, 95% of existing codebases are too messy or fragile for an AI agent to touch safely. He’s right—which is exactly why I built BigConfig. We don’t need agents to fix messy legacy code; we need a deterministic, isolated sandbox where they can deliver software safely. The 10-Minute Deployment Workflow In my latest demonstration, I show how a “Vibecoder” can go from a blank slate to a live, provisioned app in 10 minutes using Claude, BigConfig, and the Marketplace. Isolation via Docker: The agent starts in a container. This provides a “clean room” environment. The agent can only see the credentials you explicitly provide. No “lateral movement” into your other system secrets. The Marketplace of Prompts: You find a ONCE-ready app (like the BigConfig Marketplace itself) and copy a prompt. The Agent’s Job: The agent doesn’t write complex logic. It performs two specific, boring tasks: installing the local software needed and generating two files: bb.edn (the configuration) and .envrc (the environment variables). Why This is “Safe Agentic” Delivery Artur’s concern is that agents are unpredictable. BigConfig solves this by being deterministic by design. Package-Led Review: When an agent uses a BigConfig Package (like the once package), it isn’t “hallucinating” how to talk to Hetzner or Cloudflare. It is executing a workflow authored and validated by a human package creator. The “Two-Task” Guardrail: The agent focuses on validate and create. You stay in plain English; the agent operates the library. No Hidden State: BigConfig lacks a dedicated CLI binary. It’s a library consumed via Babashka tasks. This means the agent reads and writes standard Clojure configuration that is transparent, version-controllable, and easily reversible. “Sure, Alberto, your tool might be safe, but most companies’ infrastructure isn’t ready for this yet.” — Artur Mkrtchyan Artur is right about the state of most infrastructure, but BigConfig isn’t meant to “fix” a 10-year-old spaghetti monolith. It’s designed to bridge the gap for the next generation of applications—like ONCE apps—where the server, DNS, and SMTP are wired up as a single, cohesive unit. My last demo In my latest demonstration, I show how a “Vibecoder” can go from a blank slate to a live, provisioned app in 10 minutes using Claude, BigConfig, and the Marketplace. Isolation via Docker The agent starts in a container. This provides a “clean room” environment. The agent can only see the credentials you explicitly provide. No “lateral movement” into your other system secrets. Dockerfile FROM ubuntu:24.04 \n RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \\         curl \\         sudo \\         ca-certificates \\     && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/* \n RUN useradd -m -u 1001 -s /bin/bash joe \\     && echo 'joe ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL' > /etc/sudoers.d/joe \\     && chmod 0440 /etc/sudoers.d/joe \n RUN curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash \\     && mv /root/.local/share/claude /usr/local/share/claude \\     && rm /root/.local/bin/claude \\     && ln -s \"$(ls -d /usr/local/share/claude/versions/* | head -n1)\" /usr/local/bin/claude \\     && chmod -R a+rX /usr/local/share/claude \n USER joe WORKDIR /home/joe \n CMD [\"bash\"] /etc/sudoers.d/joe \\ && chmod 0440 /etc/sudoers.d/joeRUN curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash \\ && mv /root/.local/share/claude /usr/local/share/claude \\ && rm /root/.local/bin/claude \\ && ln -s \"$(ls -d /usr/local/share/claude/versions/* | head -n1)\" /usr/local/bin/claude \\ && chmod -R a+rX /usr/local/share/claudeUSER joeWORKDIR /home/joeCMD [\"bash\"]\"> docker run -it --rm -u joe -v \"$(pwd):/home/joe\" joe-ubuntu It’s Turtles All The Way Down To prove the point: The BigConfig Marketplace is itself a ONCE application. It’s a Docker image bundling a PocketBase backend with an Astro frontend. It was deployed using the same once package it catalogs. It serves HTTP on port 80, has a health check at /up, and persists state in /storage. By narrowing the contract between the code and the infrastructure, we make the environment safe enough for an agent to handle the “grunt work” of deployment. We’re moving away from “fixing the mess” and toward a world where software delivery is as simple as a conversation. Ready to try it? Browse the Marketplace , grab a prompt, and let your agent do the heavy lifting."}, :excerpts [{:text "... the agent operates the library. No Hidden State: BigConfig lacks a dedicated CLI binary. It’s a...", :matched-terms ["state"], :source :content} {:text "... This means the agent reads and writes standard Clojure configuration that is transparent,...", :matched-terms ["clojure"], :source :content} {:text "... yet.” — Artur Mkrtchyan Artur is right about the state of most infrastructure, but BigConfig isn’t meant...", :matched-terms ["state"], :source :content}]}]